The effective stability which was produced by the demise of the Somali system of state, contributed to the resurgence of Eritrean nationalism in the later half of the 1960's and the formation of the ELF by Hashim Ahmed and Ernest Akele in the United Arab Emirates in 1962.However, the implementation of the 52 years resistance almost gone depriving of its fruits of independence, resulted in the rapid reverse of the nationalistic spirit.

The bitter experience of the almost lost and finished struggle, gave birth to a fresh affirmation of nationalism and of the need for national unity. The Eritrean Liberation Front (ELF) was formed as the result of this attempt [54]. Ten years after the formation of the ELF, the other opposition - the Eritrea People's Liberation Forces (EPRLF) - established a branch office in the north and took the name of the EPLF.

In 1973, after a decade of internal division and of using tons of ammunitions fired at the wrong target, the government of Ethiopia declared that the Eritrean Front was a defeated group, and its organization was broken up and most of its cadres hunt down and killed.
